lish <i>hole(g)n</i> ‘holly (tree)’; or, especially in southern England, a habitational name from any of the places such as East and West Holme (Dorset) or Holne (Devon). Compare   Hollis  ."]},{"name":"Holmes","meanings":["English: either from the plural form of   Holme  , or else a variant of   Holme   or   Home  , with excrescent <i>-s</i> (see   Holm  ).","Scottish: probably a habitational name from Holmes near Dundonald (Ayrshire), or possibly from another place so called in the barony of Inchestuir (Angus). Both placenames likely derive from the plural form of Middle English, Older Scots <i>holm</i> ‘islet, raised land in a marsh’ (see   Holm  ).","Scottish and Irish: adopted for Scottish Gaelic and Irish <b>Mac Thómais</b>, <b>Mac Thómais</b> (see   McComb  ). In parts of western Ireland, <b>Holmes</b> is also a variant of <b>Cavish</b>, from Gaelic <b>Mac Thámhais</b>, another patronymic from   Thomas  . Early bearers in Ireland were probably immigrants from Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Olenor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(2010: NA)","Variant of   Flener   1, a surname of German origin. See also   Fleener  , compare   Fleenor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Flener","meanings":["Same as Eleanor."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Olenor Holme was born in 1124, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Holm, was 34 and his mother, Mrs. Annas Mnuk, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Rysom. He died in 1165, in Barnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1124–1165":"1124–1165","1124–Male":"1124–Surnud","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1127–1165":"1127–1165","1155–1196":"1155–1196","1090–1134":"1090–1134","1100–1134":"1100–1134","1090":"1090","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1124":"1124","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","BEF 1124":"enne 1124","1100":"1100","1165":"1165","1196":"1196","Frome, Somerset, , England":"Frome, Somerset, England",",, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","B